div.p: THE ENGLISH DICTIONARIE: OR, AN INTERPRETER of hard Engliſh Words.

Enabling as well Ladies and Gentlewomen, young Schollers, Clarkes, Merchants, as alſo Strangers of any Nation, to the vnderſtanding of the more difficult Authors already printed in our Language, and the more ſpeedy attaining of an elegant perfection of the Engliſh tongue, both in reading, ſpeaking and writing.
Being a Collection of the choiſeſt words contained in the Table Alphabeticall and Engliſh Expoſitor, and of ſome thouſands of words neuer publiſhed by any heretofore.
By H. C. Gent.
LONDON, Printed for Edmund Weauer, and are to be ſold at his ſhop at the great North gate of Pauls Church. 1623.

div.head: TO THE RIGHT HOnourable, Sir Richard Boyle, Knight, Lord Boyle, Baron of Youghall, Viſcount Dungaruan, Earle of Cork, and one of his Maieſties moſt Honourable Priuie Councell of the Kingdome of Ireland, &c.
div.p:
PArt of euery deſertfull birth, (Right Honourable) in any man his Country may challenge, his Soueraigne a part, his Parents a part, & his friends another. As I cannot be vſeful in euery reſpect to each of thoſe, ſo I will ſtriue to expreſſe at leaſt a will, if not a perfection in abilitie to all. Where a generall voice warrants an approbation, there euery ſeruice is a duty. The truth of it both concernes and inuites me, out of the fame and applauſe of your Nobleneſſe, to make a particular dedication of ſome ſerious houres to your ſuruey, whom the world ſpeakes both noble and learned, wherein as I haue done my beſt to accommodate diſcourſe
with the choiſeſt language, ſo I deſire that my ambition of being knowne vnto your Lordſhip may not be imputed either vnto an errour of impudence, or an impudence in erring. Pleaſe you to know thus much of me, that I am partly imboldned hereunto, by the aſſurance of your loue and fauours to that noble Gentleman, Sir William Hull, to whom as I am tied in double bonds of bloud and friendſhip, ſo, I am ſo much obliged vnto him, that I cannot deuiſe a better rent than to doe you ſeruice: But chiefely the report of your owne honourable merit and iuſt commendations, encourage mee to this duty, though otherwiſe vnknowne, not queſtioning but you will be pleaſed to take notice of one who loues and honours vertue in all Perſonages for vertues ſake. Vouchſafe (Right Honourable) this poore teſtimonie of my obſeruancie, intended only to ſerue you, not to inſtruct you, and you ſhall not onely largely requite my endeuours, but may alſo expect a more ſteady and particular duty from

closer.signed: Your Honours moſt ready ſeruant, Henry Cockeram.

div.head: A Premonition from the Author to the Reader.
div.p:
I Am not ignorant of the praiſe-worthy labours which ſome Schollers of deſerued memorie haue heretofore beſtowed on the like ſubiect that I haue here aduentured on: howſoeuer it might therefore ſeeme a needleſſe taske of mine, to intrude vpon a plot of ſtudy, the foundation of whoſe building hath beene formerly leuel'd and laid, yet the Iuſtice of defence herein is ſo cleere, that my endeuours may bee truly termed rather a neceſſity of doing, than an arrogancie in doing. For without appropriating to my owne comfort any intereſt of glory, the vnderſtanding Readers will not, the ignorant cannot, and the malicious dare not, but acknowledge that what any before me in this kinde haue begun, I haue not onely
fully finiſhed, but throughly perfected. To write an Apologie of iuſtification would argue rather a diſtruſt of my Worke than a confidence of merit: Be pleaſed therefore (honeſt and (therin) learned Reader) to ſuruey a ſhort Premonition for the order of the enſuing Vocabularie. Firſt the method is plaine and eaſie, being alphabeticall, by which the capacity of the meaneſt may ſoone be inlightened. The firſt Booke hath the choiſeſt words themſelues now in vſe, wherewith our language is inriched and become ſo copious, to which words the common ſenſe is annexed. The ſecond Booke containes the vulgar words, which whenſoeuer any deſirous of a more curious explanation by a more refined and elegant ſpeech ſhall looke into, he ſhall there receiue the exact and ample word to expreſſe the ſame: Wherein by the way let me pray thee to obſerue that I haue alſo inſerted (as occaſion ſerued) euen the mocke-words which are ridiculouſly vſed in our language, that thoſe who deſire a generality of knowledge may not bee ignorant of the ſenſe, euen of the fuſtian termes, vſed by too many who ſtudy rather to bee heard ſpeake, than to vnderſtand themſelues. The laſt Booke is a recitall of ſeuerall perſons, Gods and Goddeſſes, Giants and Deuils, Monſters and Serpents, Birds and Beaſts, Riuers, Fiſhes, Herbs, Stones, Trees, and the like, to the intent that the diligent learner may not pretend
the defect of any helpe which may informe his diſcourſe or practice. I might inſiſt vpon the generall vſe of this worke, eſpecially for Ladies and Gentlewomen, Clarkes, Merchants, young Schollers, Strangers, Trauellers, and all ſuch as deſire to know the plenty of the Engliſh; but I am confident, that experience will be the trueſt Herauld to publiſh to the world on my behalfe, how as my debt to my countrie is to bee challenged, ſo my Country ſhall not altogether boaſt of any immunity from being indebted to my S • udies. Thus what I haue done is (Reader) for thy benefit, accept it and make vſe of it, ſo ſhall I finde reward in my labours, and reſt thy friend,

div.head: To his very good friend, Maſter Henry Cockeram, on his Vocabulary.

lg.l: He whoſe ſelfe loue, or too ambitious ſpirit,
Enuies or carpes at this thy Muſes action,
Nere let him liue, or of a Muſe once merit
Regard or fame, but die in his detraction,
Irreuocably plagu'd with Zoilan ſpight,
Ere he once taſte of Hellicons delight.
Could I, oh could I quinteſſence my skill,
Or with Elixir truly alcumize,
Knowledge with learning ſhould inſtruct my quill
Effectually to praiſe thy Muſes guiſe,
Re-felling all the criticall diſaſters,
Among ſome captious, yet wiſe ſeeming maſters,
Made by her curious eye, their owne diſtaſters.

closer.signed: Nicholas Smith, Eques Auratus Encomiaſtes Poſthumus.

div.head: To my induſtrious friend, the Author of this Engliſh Dictionarie, Mr. HENRY COCKRAM of EXETER.

lg.l: BOrne in the Weſt? liue there? ſo far frō Court?
Frō Oxford, Cambridge, London? yet report
(Now in theſe daies of Eloquence) ſuch change
Of words? vnknown? vntaught? tis new & ſtrange.
Let Gallants therefore skip no more from hence
To Italie, France, Spaine, and with expence
Waſte time and faire eſtates, to learne new faſhions
Of complementall phraſes, ſmooth temptations
To glorious beggary: Here let them hand
This Booke; here ſtudie, reade, and vnderſtand:
Then ſhall they finde varietie at Home,
As curious as at Paris, or at Rome.
For my part I confeſſe, hadſt not thou writ,
I had not beene acquainted with more wit
Than our old Engliſh taught; but now I can
Be proud to know I haue a Countryman
Hath ſtrugled for a fame, and what is more,
Gain'd it by paths of Art, vntrod before.
The benefit is generall; the crowne
Of praiſe particular, and thats thine owne.
What ſhould I ſay? Thine owne deſerts inſpire thee,
Twere baſe to enuie, I muſt then admire thee.

closer.signed: A friend and louer of thy paines, IOHN FORD

div.head: To the Reader on this Verball of his eſteemed friend, Maſter Henry C • ckeram of Exeter.

lg.l: ARt hidden moulds, the Author freely ſends,
His ſweat of brow to publike priuat friends,
His courteſie to labour, yours to raiſe,
As it deſerues the countenance of praiſe.
Hardwords farfetch'd, made ſmooth, before being rough,
Claime fauour for requitall, that's enough.
If you betray them with a trecherous kiſſe,
He'l laugh in's ſleeue, and at your follies hiſſe.

div.head: To the Reader on this Vocabulary of his good friend, Maſter Henry Cockeram of Exeter.

lg.l: IF things farre fetch'd are deareſt, moſt eſteem'd,
which by times ſweatful houres haue been redeem'd.
Of what count's this, of which ſort like was neuer,
Praiſe it of force you muſt, and loue him euer.
The Adage is far ſought, deare bought, pleaſe ladies,
You muſt yeeld to this Maxime, or proue babies.
Then giue worths due, that worthineſſes guiſe,
If not, my Motto is, you are vnwiſe.

div.head: To my very good friend, Maſter Cokeram, Author of this worke.

lg.l: TO ſpeake good words of thee were but in part
To pay backe what we owe, for thy rare Art
Hath taught vs all good language: a rude pile
Of barbarous ſillables into a ſtile
Gentle and ſmooth thou haſt reduc't: pure gold
Thou haſt extracted out of worthleſſe mould.
And that no one may thinke thy merit weake,
Of a rough ſpeech th'aſt taught vs all to ſpeake
A perfect language; in which Cockerams praiſe
Shall liue belou'd, whilſt time leaues making daies.

div.head: To his induſtrious friend, Maſter Henry Cockeram.

lg.l: TO ouer-praiſe thy Booke, in a ſmooth line,
(If any errour's in't) would make it mine:
Onely, while Words for paiment paſſe at Court,
And whilſt loud talke and wrangling make reſort
I'th Terme to Weſtminſter, I doe not dread
Thy leaues ſhall ſcape the Scombri, and be read.
And I will adde this as thy friend, no Poet,
Thou haſt toild to purpoſe, and the euent wil ſhew it.

div.head: To his worthily reſpected friend, Maſter Henry Cockeram.

lg.l: WHo hath diſcouer'd yet a neerer way,
By which, what we conceiue, we can conuey
To others, then by words, that full expreſſe
What Mimicke action doth but onely gueſſe:
But where a language hath variety,
And euery word a reall property,
How much it adds to elocution,
As doe but reade this Booke, then thinke vpon
The Authors paines and praiſe, giue him reſpect
For this addition to our Dialect.

div.head: THE FIRST PART OF THE ENGLISH DICTIONARY.

list.head: AB
list.item: Abandon. To forſake or caſt off.
Abatement. That which is abated or abridged.
Abbet. To further one in euill.
Abbettour. Which counſelleth one to doe euill.
Abecedarian. One that teacheth the Croſſe-row.
Abgregate. To lead out of the flocke.
Abiudicated. Giuen by iudgement from one to another.

Ablecticke. Any thing
garniſhed for ſale.
Ablocate. To ſet, or let out to hire.
Abortion. The birth of a childe before his time.
Abſtract. A ſmall booke taken out of another.
Aca lemicall. Belonging to an Vniuerſitie.
Academicke. A Philoſopher of the ſect of Plato.
Acceſſe. Libertie to come to a place.
Acceſſible. Which may be come to.
Acceſſorie. Which wittingly hidet • an offender, or counſelleth him in euill
Accoſte. To draw neere to one.
Accub. The print of any creatures foot.
Acerſecomicke. One whoſe haire was neuer cut.

Acetarr •
A ſalad of ſmall herbes.

Acheruſe An entrance into Hell, from whence Hercules drew forth Cerberus the three-headed Dog of Hell with an Adamantine chaine. Poets likewiſe faine, that in this place Charon receiued the ſoules into his Boat which he caried ouer Stix, Acharon, and Phlegiton.
Aconitum. A poyſonous herbe whereon Cerberus ſpued out his poyſon when he was dragd out of Hell by Hercu • es.
Acquitall. A freeing of one from being guilty.
Action. A deed done, or a doing.
Actor. A ſtage player, or one doing a thing.
Adamantine. Hard, not to be broken.
Addition. The ſame that Additament is.
Adecaſticke. One that will doe iuſt howſoeuer.
Adhalate. To breath or blow on.
Adhere. To ſticke or cleaue to.
Adiourne. To defer, to put off.
Adiournament. When a Court is diſſolued.
Adiunct. A qualitie ioyned to a thing, as heat to fire, or the like.
Adiuration. A ſwearing, or binding by oath.
Adminiſter. To diſpoſe of a dead mans goods.
Adminiſtration. The diſpoſing of a dead mans goods, which made no will.
Adminiſtrator. He to whō the Ordinarie committeth in charge the goods of a dead man ſo dying.

Adminiſtratrix. A woman
in that place.
Admixtion. A mingling of things together.
Adoleſcenturate. To play the boy, or foole.
Adopt. To chuſe one to be his ſonne.
Adoption. The chuſing of one to be his ſonne.
Adriaticke Sea. The gulfe of Venice.
Aduent. The comming of certaine weekes before Chriſtmas: ſo called, for then in the Church is made ſolemne preparation for Chriſts comming.

Aduertiſe. To giue kno •
ledge of a thing.
Aduocate. Which pleadeth for another in a Conſiſtorie.
Advouſon. Right which a man hath to preſent a Clergie man to a ſpirituall Benefice.
Aeriall Of or belonging to the aire.
AEſtiuate. To ſummer in a place.
AEſti • all. Of or belonging to Sum • er.
Affec • ation. An inordinate deſire which we haue.
Affrica. The South part of the world.
Aff • icke bird. A coward, one in gay cloathes.
Agent. A doer, or medler in a thing.
Aggerate. A doer, or medler in a thing.
Agglutinate. To ioyne or glue together.
Aggrauate. To make a thing worſe by words.
Aggreſſion. An aſſault, a ſetting vpon.
Agitate. To toſſe, iogg, or ſhake.
Agnate. A kinſman by the fathers ſide.
Agnation. Kindred by the fathers ſide.
Agonalics. Feaſts at which there were great exerciſes of actiuitie.
Agonie. Torment of bodie and minde.
Agonotheth. A Iudge in maiſteries of actiuitie.
Agroſe. One which hath much lands.
Alablaſter. A very cold marble white and cleare.

Alchymie. The Art of melting or diſſoluing mettals
by ſeparating the pure from the impure.
Allegorie. A ſentence that muſt be vnderſtood otherwiſe than the literall interpretation ſhewes.
Allie. Of kin to one by mariage.
Alligate. To bind or tie vp.
Allude. To ſpeake any thing which hath reſemblance to another thing.
Alluſion. A reſembling of one thing to another.
Alloes. A pretious wo • d vſed in Phyſicke.
Aloeſucotrena. The iuyce of an herbe, being an excellent medicine to purge choler.
Alopick. One that hath no haire on his head.
Alpha. The firſt letter of the Greekes.
Altercation. An angry reaſoning in words.
Allutation. A tanning or dreſſing of leather.
Ama • hean borne. Plenty of all things.
Ambage. A long circumſtance of words.
Ambergreiſe. As ſome write, is the ſpawne of a Whale, the fume thereof good to comfort the braine.
Ambidexter. One that can vſe both hands alike, or a ſubtle knaue.
Ambition. Pride, immoderate deſire of ſoueraigntie.
Ambroſia. After the Poets, the meat of the Gods.
Ambuate. To moue hither and thither.
Ambulatorie. A place to walke in.
Ambuſcado. Souldiers hid in a ſecret place to entrap the enemie.
Ambuſhment. A ſecret lying to entrap one.
Amerce. To puniſh one by making him pay ſome ſmall ſumme of money.
Amercement. A puniſhment by the purſe.
Amoniſcorne. A gemme of a gold colour like a Rams horne, which cauſeth one to dreame true things.
Amphibolie. A ſpeech which may be taken many wayes.
Amphitheater. A place made hauing ſeats.
Amphit • hami. A chamber hauing a chamber on both ſides.
Anagnoſticke. A Curate ſeruing only to reade.
Anagogick. One skild in explaining the Scriptures.
Anagram. An inuention by altering the places of the letters of ones name to make another word, as of Iude, to make vide.
Analects. Crums which fall from the table.
Analogie. Proportion, likeneſſe of one thing to another.
Analyſis. A reſolution in doubtfull matters.
Anarchie. When a kingdome is without a King.
Anathematize. To giue ones ſelfe to the Deuill.
Anatomie. The trunke of a dead man, from whence all the fleſh is cut off with the ſinewes, and nothing remaining ſaue the bare bones.
Anat • mize. To cut and ſearch euery part, to make an Anatomie.
Anchoreſſe. A religious woman, liuing ſolitarie.
Anchorite. A religious man, liuing ſolitarie.
Androgine. He that is both man and woman.
Animaduerſion. A marking, a har • ning.
Annales. Chronicles from yeere to yeere.
Annates. The firſt fruits paid of a ſpirituall liuing.
Annex. To knit or ioyne to.
Anniuerſarie. A ſolemnity kept from yeere to yeere.
Annuate. To nod with the head.
Annuitie. Yeerely payment of money to one.
Annulet. Any thing hanging about the necke.
Anomalie. Vnequalitie, vnlikeneſſe to any thing.
Antarticke pole. The South pole of the world.
Anthemne. A Song which Church-men ſing by courſe one after another.
Anthropophagize. One man to kill and eat anothers fleſh.
Antelucidate. To worke by candle light before day.
Antiloquie. A terme which Stage-players vſe by them called theire cue.
Antidate. A dating of ſome letter or other writing on ſome day paſt.
Antitheſis. Contrarieties of things placed one againſt another, as ſpokes in a wheele.
Aphoriſme. A ſhort ſentence briefly expreſſing the properties of a thing.
Apolactize. To ſpurne with the heele.
Apologicall. He which maketh an excuſe.
Apoſtata. He which falleth from true Religion.
Apoſtle. One ſent in a meſſage, a meſſenger.
Apothegme. A quick, ſhort and witty ſentence.
Apparitor. A Sumner, ſummoning one to a Court.
Appeale. When a malefactor accuſeth his conſort.
Appendix. Which dependeth on another thing, a waiter.
Applaud. To ſhew liking to a thing by clapping of hands.
Applauſe. A clapping of hands for ioy.
Application. An applying of one thing to another.
Appropriate. To challange to ones ſelfe.
Appropriation. When a priuate man hath right to a Parſonage in himſelfe, and may receiue the profit thereof by maintaining a Vicar to ſerue the place.
Aprication. A beaking in the Sunne.
Apricitie. The warmenes of the Sunne in winter.
Arbiter. A Iudge in ſome controuerſies, choſen indifferently for both parties.
Arbitrament. An agreement made betwixt two parties.
Archiatrer. A chiefe or principall Phyſitian.
Architype. The chiefe or firſt patterne.
Arduitie. High, hardneſſe to come to.
Aretalogon. A vaunter of his owne vertues.
Argent. Siluer, or of ſiluer colour.
Ariſtocracie. A kinde of gouernment where the Nobilitie beare all the ſway.
Ariſtocraticall. Of or belonging to Ariſtocracie.
Aromaticke wine. Sweet wine brewed with ſpices: Hippocras.
Arrogate. Proudly to challenge to himſelfe more honour than is due.
Artemiſean moneth. The moneth of May.
Arteries. Hollow ſinewes or veines, wherein the ſpirits of life doe walke.
Articulate. To ſet downe articles or conditions of agreement.
Artick pole. The North pole of the world.
Artiſt. One skild in any Arte.
Aruſpicie. Diuination by opening the bowels of beaſts.
Aſa-foetida. A dried gum hauing a very ſtrong and loathſome ſmell.
Aſpire. To hope to come to a thing.
Aſſaſſinate. To rob or murther in the high way.
Aſſets. When a man hath goods come to his hand to diſcharge a dead mans debts or legacies giuen by him.
Aſſignement. A paſſing of one thing ouer to another.
Aſſociation. A ioyning together in fellowſhip.
Aſſoile. To acquite or diſcharge, to pardon.
Aſſonate. To ſound or ring like a bell.
Aſſumpſit. When one for ſome conſideration giuen doth vndertake to doe any thing.
Aſſumption. A taking or lifting vp.
Aſtrictiue. Which hath power to binde.
Aſtrologie. A foretelling of things to come.
Aſtronomie. An Arte teaching the knowledge of the courſes both of Planets and Starres.
Atcheeuement. The performance of any great matter.
Atheiſme. The damnable opinion of the Atheiſts.
Atheiſt. That thinks there is no God, or rule of religion.
Atomie. A mote flying in the Sunne beames: any thing ſo ſmall that it cannot be made leſſe.
Atrate. One clad in blacke, a mourner.
Atricke. An Vſher of a Hall.
Attainted. Conuicted of ſome great crime.
Attenuate. To diminiſh or make leſſe.
Atturney. He that by mutuall conſent taketh charge of another mans buſineſſe.
Atturnment. The paying of a ſmall peece of monie by a Tenant in token that he acknowledgeth the partie to whom he payeth it, his Landlord.
Audience. A hearing: ſometime it ſignifieth an aſſembly of people.
Aueruncate. To take away that which hurts, to weed.
Auerment. Approuing a thing to be true and honeſt.
Auguration. Diuination by flying of birds in the aire.
Auoke. To fall from, or backe againe.
Auowable. That which may be iuſtified.
Aurigation. A driuing of a Coach.
Auſtere. Sharpe, cruell.Auſteritie. Hard viſage, cruelty.
Autonomie. Libertie to liue after ones owne law.
Axiome. A maxime or ſentence allowed to be true.

list.head: B.
list.item: Badger. One that buyes corne or other victuall in one place to tranſport it to another, for gaine.
Balme, or Balſamum. An excellent medicine for a greene wound, and diuers other purpoſes.
Bandle. An Iriſh meaſure of two foot in length.
Baptiſme. A waſhing or dipping in water.
Barbariſme. Rudeneſſe in ſpeech or behauiour.
Barreſter. One allowed to plead at a barre.
Barricado. A warlike defence made with empty barrels.
Barriers. A warlike exerciſe of men fighting with ſhort ſwords, and within ſome appointed compaſſe.
Baſſaw. A noble man in Turkie.
Baſtion. A defence built within a City.
Benefactor. A friend, one that doth one good.
Beuie. A troope of Ladies, Quailes, or of Deere.
Bezell. The broad place of a Ring where the ſtone is ſet.
Bigamie. The Marriage of two wiues.
Blephoron. One hauing great browes and eye-lids.
Blomarie. The firſt forge through which the yron paſſeth after it is melted out of the Mine.
Boone. A requeſt, ſometime good, as a boone companion.
Boras. A white ſubſtance like ſalt-peeter wherewith goldſmiths ſolder gold and ſiluer.
Brachigraphy. A ſhort kind of writing, as a letter for a word.
Braket. Drinke made of hony, ſpice, and water.
Brandiſh. To ſhake properly a ſword, or the like.
Brigantine. A kind of a ſmall ſhip.
Brocage. Meanes vſed by a ſpokeſ-man.
Brocket. A red Deere of two yeeres old.
Brumall. Of or belonging to winter.
Bubulcitate. To cry like a cow boy.
Bucentaure. A carricke or great ſhip.
Burglarie. A breaking into a houſe by night with an intent to ſteale and murder.
Burnet. An attire for the head, a hood.
Burniſh. By rubbing to make a thing glitter.
Burſholder. An officer in a borough.
Buttreſſes. Staies to prop vp a wall.

list.head: C
list.item: CAbal. The traditions of the Iewes doctrine of religion.
Caball. A little horſe, a lade.
Cacuminate. To make ſharpe or copped.
Cadence. The falling of the voyce.
Calamiſt. One hauing his haire turning vpward.
Calculate. To reckon, to caſt account.
Calthrate. To ſtop with barres of lettice.
Calthrope. A little thing made with foure prickes of iron, of ſuch a faſhion that which way ſoeuer it bee throwne, one point will alway ſticke vp like a naile to ſpoile the foot of the enemies horſe.
Caluarie. A place for dead mens bones.
Camelionize. To change into many colours.
Camphire. A gum very cold and drie.
Cancell. To deface, to blot out.
Canicular dayes. Dog daies, verie hot daies in Iuly and Auguſt: ſo called of the Starre Canis the dog, which then riſeth with the Sun, and doth much encreaſe his heat.
Canonier. One which ſhooteth in great Ordnance.
Canonize. To pronounce • ne to be a Saint.
Cape. A corner of a land ſhooting out into the ſea.
Capite. When one holds land immediately from the Crowne.
Capitoll. An ancient pallace in Rome ſo called.
Capitulate. To draw or bring into Chapters.
Capnomancie. Diuination by flying of ſmoake.
Capricorne. A ſigne containing twentie ſtarres.
Capriole. The leaping of a horſe aboue ground, called by horſemen the goats leape.
Capſtand. An inſtrument to wind vp things of great weight.
Carbonado. A raſher vpon the coales.
Carbunculate. To burne like a cole.
Carreere. A ſhort ſwift race with a horſe.
Carrick. A great ſhip of burden.
Caſtalides. The ſurname of the Muſes.
Catalogue. A roll, a bill, a regiſter of names.
Cataract. A diſtillation of humours out of the eyes.
Catarrhe. A diſtillation of watrie humours out of the head.
Cataſtrophe. The end of a comedie, a ſudden alteration.
Cataſtrophize. To end a comedie, or the like.
Cataſtrum. The decke or hatch of a ſhip.
Catamite. A boy which is vſed for buggery.
Cathedrall. Of or belonging to a Biſhops chayre.
Catoptromancie. Diuination by viſions ſhewen in a glaſſe.
Cauerne. A hole or caue in the earth.
Cauſidicke. A lawyer, atturney, aduocate, or procter.
Celebrate. To doe a thing in honour of ſome one.
Celebration. The ſolemnization of a feaſt.
Cenſor. A graue officer hauing power to correct matters.
Center. The point in the midſt of a round circle, and therefore the earth is called the center of the world becauſe it is in the middeſt thereof.
Centurion. A Captaine of one hundred men.
Cermocinatrix. Shee that inſtructed to ſpeake.
Certificate. A writing auerring the truth of a thing.
Champertaurs. Such as ſtir other to law bearing their charges, to ſhare part of what they ſue for.
Chancellor. A chiefe officer in a ſpirituall court.
Chaos. A confuſed and diſordered heap, whereof poets faine the world, and all that therein is to bee made.
Character. The forme of a letter.
Charibdis. A gulfe in the ſea, wherein is moſt dangerous ſayling by reaſon of contrarie windes.
Charls-waine. Certaine ſtarres winding about the North Pole of the world in faſhion like foure wheeles and horſes drawing it.
Charnall houſe. A place to lay ſculls & dead bones in.
Charter. A writing of priuiledge and liberties.
Chirographicall. Writing, a writing of ones owne hand.
Chorographie. The deſcription of a countrey.
Chriſme. A white linnen cloth wrapped about an infant after it is newly chriſtened.
Chronologie. The knowledge of old ſtories.
Chymaeras. Strange phantaſies, caſtles in the ayre.
Chyromancie. Di • ination by the palme of the hand.
Cimball. An old muſicall inſtrument made with plates of braſſe.
Circular. That which is round in compaſſe.
Circumciſe. To cut off the foreskin of ones priuitie.
Circumciſion. A cutting off the foreskin.
Circumlocution. A ſpeaking of many words.
Circumplicate. To roll or wrap about.
Circumſcribe. To draw a line about.
Circumſcriptible. Which may bee limited within bands.
Cite. To warne one to appeare.
Citharize. To play on the harpe.
Citadell. A caſtle with a ſmall garriſon to keepe a towne in awe.
Client. One asking counſell of a Lawyer.

Clymactericall. Is euerie ſeuenth yeere, which is held very dangerous, and by this account the 14, 21, 28, 35, &c. are held clymactericall yeeres: ſome hold the ninth yeere to be the clymactericall yere, & as dangerous as the other: and by this account 18, 27, 36, &c. are ſo called: But the moſt dangerous and notedſt climactericall yeere is at the age of 63. for that both accounts doe meet in this number, namely, 9. times ſeuen, and 7. times 9. either of which numbers make 63. this (I ſay) is held the moſt dangerous yeere of all.
Climate. Sgnifieth a portion of the world between North and South, containing ſome notable difference in the ſunne riſing.
Cluck. To call like a hen.
Coagulate. To turne to a curd.
Coequall. Equall in degree with another.
Coeſſentiall. Of the ſame eſſence or ſubſtance.
Coelanes. Of one time and age.
Cohere. To agree, ſticke, or hang together.

Collaterall. Sidewaies: euerie degree of kindred is either lineall or collaterall: the lineall is that which commeth from the grandfather to the father, and from the father to the ſonne, and ſo ſtill right downewards: collaterall is that which commeth ſidewaies, as firſt between brothers and ſiſters, then betweene their children, &c. Alſo vncles, aunts, and all couſens are contained vnder this terme of collaterall kindred.
Collimate. To leuell or winke with one eye.

Colon. A marke of a ſentence not fully ended: it is
thus made with two pricks (:) thus.
Coloquintida. A kinde of wild gourd, it is often vſed in Phyſicke.
Coloſſe. A huge Image or ſtatue made of wood: wee read of one in the Ile of Rhodes, whoſe thumbe few men could fathome.
Columbate. To bill or kiſſe like a Doue.
Combate. A fight between two allowed by the law, for the triall of ſome controuerſie.
Combatant. Hee which is to fight a Combate.
Combuſtible. That which will ſoone be ſet on fire.
Comedie. A Play or Enterlude, whoſe beginning is full of trouble, the end thereof is mirth and ioy.
Comedian. A Player or Writer of Come •• es.
Comma. A marke made (,) oft vſed in writing.
Commaſculate. To ſet one in ſtomacke.
Commence. To enter an Action againſt one
Comment. A lye or tale, ſometimes a note of inſtruction ſet in the margent of a Book to expound that which is hard to bee vnderſtood.

Commiſſion. A writing, ſhewing that one or many
haue ſome authority in matters of truſt commited to their charge.
Commiſſioner. That hath authority by commiſſion.
Committe. He to whom a matter is committed to be ordered or decided.
Commotrix. A maid that makes ready and vnready her Miſtris.
Communicable. That which may bee imparted to another.
Compact. Hard or cloſe knit together.
Compaginate. To ſet together that which is broken.
Compendium. A ſauing courſe, a ſhort way.
Competitor. One ſuing for the ſame thing another doth.
Compile. To make or ſet together.
Complexion. The temperature of the humors in ones body, which cauſeth the colour.
Compoſe. To frame, to ſet together.
Compoſition. A ioyning or ſetting together.
Comprehend. To conceiue in the minde.
Comprehenſible. That which may be conceiued.
Compremiſe. An agreement made by indifferent men choſen on both ſides.
Compunction. A ſticking in the ſide.
Comrade. A companion, a good fellow.
Concoction. A digeſtion of meat in the bodie.
Condeſcend. To ioyne together, to agree.
Conduce. To bring with, to helpe.
Conduct. To guide one in the way.
Confabulate. To talke, to tell tales.
Confection. A mingling, or what is mingled.
Confederate. One linked with another in ſomething.
Conferre. To talke together, to compare together.
Confines. The borders of a City.
Confiſcate. Seiſed on to the Kings vſe, forfeited.
Confluence. A flowing together, great ſtore.
Conforme. To frame ones ſelfe to what is required of one.
Confute. To diſproue or ouerthrow by Argument.
Congeale. To freeze, to grow ſtiffe with cold.
Conglomerate. To winde vp on bottomes.
Conglutinate. To ioyne or glew together.
Congratulate. To reioyce in anothers behalfe.
Congratulation. A reioycing in ones behalfe.
Coniecturall. Which may or may not be, vncertaine.
Coniure. To ſweare, to bind by oath.
Conniue. To winke at a thing.
Conniuence. A winking at a matter.
Conſequent. Neceſſarily comming after another thing.
Conſerues. The iuyce or ſubſtance kept of things which are boyled with ſugar, &c.
Conſiſtorie. A iudgement-place, or aſſembly of Iudges.
Conſolidate. To make firme or ſound.
Conſonant. Agreeable: alſo, euery letter that is no vowell, as b. c. d. are ſo called.
Conſort. A companion, or Muſitians together.
Conſtellation. A company of ſtarres together.
Conſtuprate. Carnally to accompany a woman.
Conſtruction. A ioyning of words together.
Conſubſtantiality. Agreement in ſubſtance.Conſull. A chiefe Romane officer: there were two yeerely choſen.
Conſumption. A diſeaſe conſuming away the body.
Contemplation. A beholding in ones mind.
Contemplate. To behold in the mind.Contemptible. Vile, baſe.
Continent land. Main land, no Iland.
Contingent. Caſual, which may and may not be.
Controuert. To ſtriue or contend about things.
Contund. To beat ſmall in a morter, to pownd.
Conuent. To bring one before a Iudge.
Conuenticle. A ſmall aſſembly commonly for ill things
Conuerſion. Turning from ill to good.
Conuiction. A proofe of being guiltie.

Conuocation. An aſſembly,
or calling together.
Convulſion. The ſhrinking together of the ſinewes.
Cor. A meaſure of a po • tle.
Corbets. Places in walls where images ſtand.
Cordial. That which comforteth the heart, heartie.
Coronell. A Captaine ouer many bands.
Coronation. A crowning of King or Queene.
Corporall. Of or belonging to the bodie.
Corporation. A bodie politike, hauing by the Kings grant a common ſeale, a chiefe officer, and inferior perſons belonging to it.
Corrade. To rake, ſhaue or ſcrape.

Correllatiues. Words which cannot be ſpoken, but there muſt be ſuppoſed ſome other word which is neceſſarily a dependant vpon it; as a father and a ſonne, a captaine and a ſouldier, a husband and a wife, &c.
Corriuall. Hee which is a ſuiter with another for mariage to a woman.
Corroge. To gather of euery ſide.
Coſignificatiue. Of the ſame ſignification with another thing.

Coſmographie. An Art
touching the deſcription of the World.
Couent. The whole company of religious men dwelling in one houſe together.
Couerture. The time that man and Wife liue together in holy Wedlocke, a couering.
Countermand. A commandment giuen contrary to a former command.
Countermine. To digge in the earth againſt another.
Countermure. A wall made in defence againſt another
Counterpane. A fellow copie of a deed.
Counterpoyſe. Which is laid in weight againſt anotherthing.
Counteruaile. To be of equall value to another thing.
Cranies. Little chinks or holes in the earth.
Credible. That which may be beleeued.
Creditor. Which lendeth mony or wares.
Credulous. Which eaſily beleeueth a thing.
Creſſant. The moone (or any thing elſe) growing.

Criticall daies. Daies wherin Phyſitians giue iudgement of the continuance
of ones ſicknes, death, or recouery.
Crociate. To cry like a rauen.
Crowd. A great throng of people.
Cubite. The meaſure of a mans elbow, to the top of his middle finger.
Cucubate. To cry like an owle.
Cucuriate. To crow like a cocke.
Cullion. The ſtone of any liuing thing.
Curfew. A bell that rings about bed time.
Curtilage. Any piece of ground ioyning to a houſe.
Cypher. A circle in Arithmetique, like the letter (o)
Cyrne. A goblet to drinke wine in.

list.head: D
list.item: Deaurate. To gild, to gliſter gold-like.
Debacchate. To reuile one after the manner of drunkards.
Deboyſt fellow. A lewd ſcum of the earth.
Decapulate. To poure out from one thing to another.
Decide. To determine a matter in controuerſie.
Decipher. To write after a ſtrange maner that none ſhall read it: alſo to find out the meaning of a thing ſo written.
Deciſion. An end of a matter in controuerſie.
Declamation. A ſpeech purpoſely made in diſpraiſe of ſome thing.
Declaymer. Hee that maketh a declamation.
Decorate. To decke, to grace, or trim.
Decorticate. To peele off the barke of a tree, or the like.
Deculcate. To tread ſomthing vnder foot.
Decuriate. To diuide into bands, to ſeparate.
Decuriation. A making of Knights or Captaines.
Decurſion. A running of ſouldiers on their enemies.
Dedecorate. To diſhonor, or ſhame one.
Dedication. A giuing, an offering vp.
Dedoleate. To end ones ſorrow or griefe.
Defaecate. To take away • ees or dregs.
Defalcate. To diminiſh or take away.
Defeaſance. An vndoing of what was formerly done.
Defect. A failing or wanting of any thing.
Defectiue. Faultie, want of any thing.
Defendant. Which anſwereth to a challenge, or accuſation.
Defenſiue. Done or ſpoken in defence.
Define. To declare a thing plainely.
Definition. A declaration what a thing is.
Definitiue. Which declareth, or concludeth a matter.
Deflectings. Turnings from good to bad.
Deflaccate. To weare out a thing.
Defomicate. To chip bread, or ſo.
Defuſt. To cudgle or beat one.
Degenerate. To turne out of kind.
Deglabrate. To pull off skin, hayre, or the like.
Degrade. To take away the priuiledge of holy Orders from one.
Degradation. A taking away of Eccleſiaſticall Orders.
Degreſſe. To vnlight from a Horſe.
Degulate. To conſume in belly cheere.
Dehortation. A perſwaſion from doing ſome thing.
Deiect. To abaſe, or throw downe.
Delation. An accuſation, or ſecret complaint.
Delegate. To aſſigne, to ſend in commiſſion.
Delian twins. The Sunne and Moone.
Delibate. To ſippe, or kiſſe the cup.
Delibrate. To pull off the rinde of a Tree.
Delimate. To file or ſhaue from off a thing.
Delineate. To drawe the firſt proportion of a thing.
Delitigate. To skold, or chide vehemently.
Deluge. An vniuerſall ouerflowing of waters: Noahs floud.
Delumbate. To beate, weaken, to breake.
Demeane. To behaue, or carrie ones ſelfe.
Demigration. A changing of places, or houſes.
Democracie. Rule which people haue ouer themſelues without a ſuperiour, vnleſſe ſuch as they themſelues will appoint.
Demoniack. One poſſeſt with a Diuel.
Denizen. A ſtranger made free by the Kings Letters Parents.
Denounce. To threaten, to giue warning.
Deoccate. To harrow, or clod the Land.

Deodand. When by a horſe, cart, bull, or the like, a man is caſually kild, &c. that which moued, and was cauſe of his death, being
forfeited to the King, belongeth to the Kings Almoner to beſtow it in deeds of charitie, and therfore cald a Deodand, as giuen away for Gods ſake.
Depalmate. To giue one a box on the eare.
Depend. To hang vpon another thing.
Dependant. Which hangeth on another thing.
Depilate. To pull off haires, or the like.

Deplum •
To pull off feathers of a thing.
Depopulate. To ſpoile or waſte a countrey.
Depoſe. To ſweare, to thruſt one out of his kingdome, or ſo.
Depoſition. An oath, or a depoſing from authoritie.
Depriuation. A loſſe of any thing.
Deproperate. To make too much ſpeed.
Depulſe. To driue away, to thruſt one often away.
Deriue. To take or draw from another thing.
Derogation. A taking away of ones honour, or ſo.
Derogatorie. That which impaireth any thing of his credit.
Deſcribe. Plainely to expreſſe a thing.
Deſecate. To mow or cut off.
Deſection. A mowing or cutting off.
Deſignement. A purpoſe which one intends to doe.
Deſpume. To take vp the ſcum of a thing.
Deſubulate. To pierce with a nale.
Deſticate. To cry like a rat.
Detraction. A ſpeaking ill of one.
Detrectation. A refuſing to doe a thing.
Detruncate. To cut, or lop boughs.
Deuaſtation. A waſting of a countrey.
Deuiant. Farre out of the way.
Dexter. Belonging to the right hand.
Diabeticall diſeaſe. When one cannot but piſſe.
Diagrafficall art. The art of painting, or caruing.
Diagramme. The title of a Booke.
Dialect. A difference of certaine words in a language, as here in England, the North Dialect differs from the Southern, and the Weſtern Dialect differs from them both.
Dialecticall. Of, or belonging to the art of Logicke.
Dialogue. A conference between two or more men in a Booke or writing.
Diameter. A ſtrait line paſſing betweene the midſt of a figure diuiding it into two equall parts.
Diapaſon. A concord in muſicke of all.
Diaper. A fine kinde of Linnin, not wouen after the common faſhion, but in certaine workes.
Dicacitie. Much babling, or ſcoulding, ſcoffing.
Dictate. To endite what another writes.
Dictatrix. A woman commanding things to be don.
Dictator. A chiefe Officer in Rome, neuer choſen but in great danger of the Eſtate of their Commonwealth.
Diffarreation. A ſacrifice done betwixt a man & his wife at a diuorcement.
Digama. She that hath two husbands.
Digreſſe. To goe from a matter.
Digreſſion. A going from a matter.
Dilacerate. To teare in peeces, to ſpoyle.
Dilemma. An argument which both wayes conuinceth ones aduerſarie, as thus, If he be a good man, why ſpeake you ill of him? If he be naught, why doe you keepe him companie?
Dimediate. To part into two parts.
Diſappeare. To vaniſh out of ſight.
Diſauow. To denie, or refuſe by vow.
Diſcalceate. To put off ones Shoes.
Diſc • ptator. A Iudge in a matter.
Diſciple. One that learneth, a Scholler.
Diſcuſſe. To examine, debate, to trie a matter.
Diſcuſſion. An examining or triall of a thing.
Disfranchiſe. To make one loſe his freedome.
Disfranchiſement. A taking away of ones freedome.
Diſgorge. To rid the ſtomacke, to ſpue.
Diſheuelled. Bare headed, the haire hanging downe about the eares.
Diſparadized. Falne from happineſſe to miſerie.
Diſparates. Words which are differing one from another, but not contrarie, as heat and cold are contraries, but heat and moiſture diſparates: viz. two contrarie qualities.
Diſſolue. To melt, to plucke downe.
Diſſolution. A pulling aſunder, a breaking.
Diſſociable. Not to bee brought to good fellowſhip.
Diſtinction. A note or marke of difference.
Diſtinguiſh. To put a difference betweene things.
Diſtracted. Mad, out of his wits.
Diſtreſſe. Miſerie, goods taken for not paying rent.
Diuage. To wander from place to place.
Diuaricate. To ſtep, to ſtride wide.
Diuination. A foretelling of what will happen.
Diuine. To foreſhew a thing to come.
Diuorce. A ſeparation of man and wife.
Diurnall. Of or belonging to the day.
Dogmaticall. Which is held in ſome mens opinion.
Dogmatiſt. Which breedeth a ſect or opinion.

row.cell: One of the houſe, or any thing belonging thereto.

list.item: Domineere. To beare rule, or great ſway.
Dominicall. Belonging to the Lords day.
Donee. He to whom a gift is giuen.
Dormatorie. A place to ſleepe in.
Drile. To trickle downe the Face, or the like.
Duall. Of, or belonging to two.
Ductible. Eaſie to be perſwaded, or drawne.
Duell. A ſingle fight, or combate.
Dulia. Seruice of a bondman, worſhip to Saints.
Dynaſticke. One of great rule and power.

list.head: E.
list.item: EAglet. Yong, childiſh, a yong Eagle.
Ebonie. Blacke Timber, good for many purpoſes.
Eccleſiaſticall. Of, or belonging to the Church.
Eccleſiaſticus. Of, or belonging to a Preacher.
Ecclipſe. Want of any light, chiefly of the Sunne and Moone.
Ecclipticke • line. A line in which the Sunne alwayes keeps his courſe, which line runs through the midſt of the twelue Signes.
Eclogs. Shepheards poems, commonly containing the talke.
Edecimate. To chuſe out the tenth man.
Eden. Paradiſe, a place of pleaſure.
Edentation. A pulling out of Teeth.
Edifie. To build, or to inſtruct.
Edition. A publiſhing, a ſetting forth.
Edormiate. To ſleepe out ones fill.
Educate. To bring vp, to nouriſh.
Effector. Which hath done a thing.
Effectrix. She which hath done ſome thing.
Effectuate. To performe or doe a thing.
Effigies. Ones picture, or ones true reſemblance.
Efflagitate. To demand a thing earneſtly.
Egerminate. To ſpring, or bud out.
Eiulation. A howling, or crying out.
Eiurate. To forſweare, or reſigne ones place.
Elaborate. To do a thing with great paines.
Elate. To lift vp, or proud, loftie.
Electuarie. A medicine made with ſirrups and powders.
Elegie. A mournefull ſong vſed at funeralls.
Element. The firſt matter of viſible ſubſtance, from whence all things take their beginning, whereof there be foure, Fire, Aire, Water, and Earth.
Elementarie. Of or belonging to the Elements.
Eliquament. Fatneſſe of fiſh, or fleſh.
Elucubrate. To doe a thing by candlelight.
Eluſcate. To make blind of one eye.
Elyſian. Of or belonging to Elyſium.
Elyſium. A pleaſant place beneath, where Poets fained the ſoules of good men did reſt.
Emaculate. To make cleane, to take out ſpots.
Emarginate. To take away the ſcurfe from the mouth of a wound.
Embaſſie. A meſſage from a Prince.
Embezill. To ſteale, or conuey away.
Embleme. A picture commōly painted or ſhadowed, comprehending ſome matter to be learned by it.
Embolning. A toſſing or heauing vp like the ſea.
Embryon. A child in the mothers wombe, ere it haue perfect ſhape.
Embrued. Stained with bloud, or ſo.
Emedull. To declare, to take out the marrow.
Emendicate. To beg, or craue almes.
Empannell. To make vp a Iurie of twelue men.
Emperick. A Phyſician onely by practiſe.
Emphaſis. A moſt plaine ſignification of ones mind.
Emphaticall. That which is vttered with moſt expreſſe ſignification.
Empyriall Heauen. The higheſt heauen aboue the firmament.
Emulation. Enuie, a ſtriuing to doe what another doth.
Enchiridion. A little book which one may ſtill carrie in ones hand.
Enchayned. Bound to one greatly for benefits receiued.
Endorſe. To write on the backſide of any thing.
Endromite. An Iriſh mantle, or ſome winter garment.
Enigma. A riddle, or darke ſpeech.
Ennean number. The number of nine.
Enormitie. A going out of rule.
Enqueſt. A Iury of twelue or more men.
Enſigne. A Flag, or any thing ſeruing for a marke of dignitie.
Enucleate. To declare, to take out the kernell.
Epact. A certaine number to find the age of the Moone by.
Epha. A meaſure contayning ten Pottles.
Ephebean. One marriageable at fifteene yeeres.
Ephi. A meaſure contayning fiue Pecks.
Ephod. A holy garment, worne by the high Prieſt.
Epicure. One giuen to exceſſe of gluttonie.
Epigrammes. Wittie and ſhort Poems, which vnder a fained name doe couertly praiſe or taxe ſome particular perſon, or thing.
Epilogue. A ſpeech made to the end of an enterlude, the concluſion or end of any thing.
Epilogize. to make a concluſion, or end.
Epiphanie. An appearing: the feaſt of Twelfe day.
Epiaedean Song. A Song ſung, ere the corps bee buried.
Epiſcopall. Of, or belonging to a Biſhop.
Epithete. An addition to a Noune Subſtantiue.
Epitome. A ſhort gathering of a matter in writing.
Epitomize. Briefely to touch: to make a ſhort gathering.
Equeſter. A place where men may ſit to ſee playes.
Equiculus. A little Horſe: the Horſe of Bacchus.

Equinoctiall line. A line paſſing in the midſt betweene the two Poles of Heauen, to which line the Sunne comming twice a yeere, namely, about the eleuenth of March, and the
eleuenth of September maketh the daies and nights of equall length.
Equiperation. A compariſon made with another.
Equiuocate. To deceiue one by reſeruing a certaine ſecret in ones minde of what is ſpoken.
Equiuocation. A ſpeech or anſwer made with a ſecret meaning reſerued in ones minde.
Equiuoke. When one word ſignifies two things.
Eradicate. To pull vp by the rootes.
Erogate. To giue where neede is, being asked.
Eromancie. Diuination by things in the ayre.
Erration. A wandring to and fro.
Eſcheate. Forfeited to the Kings vſe, or chiefe Lord.
Eſcheater. Which certifieth into the Exchequor, ſuch things as doe eſchea • vnto the King.
Eſcuage. A tenure of Lands, whereby the Tenant is bound at his owne charge to follow his Lord into the warres: ſometime he onely payeth an yeerely rent.
Eſſence. The naturall ſubſtance of any thing being.
Eſſentiall. Belonging to the eſſence of a thing.
Eſſoynd. When a man by leaue may abſent himſelfe from a Court.
Eſtimate. To cenſure or iudge of.
Eſtreate. A Coppy taken of any writings.
Eſtouers. Plots of wood, where its lawfull for any Tenant to take fuell, and timber to repaire their tenements.
Eſtuate. To boile and bubble like the Sea.
Etheriall. Heauenly, belonging to the Spheares.
Etymologie. The true expoſition of a word.
Euangeliſt. A bringer of good tydings.
Euaporate. To conſume away in ſmoake.
Euent. The ende of a thing, ſucceſſe.
Euentilate. To winnow, or blow winde.
Euiction. An ouerthrow in Law, when the buyer is compelled to rid his hands of the thing, that was by him gotten and purchaſed, becauſe that the ſeller had no intereſt in the thing.
Euiration. A gelding of a man.
Europe. This part of the world, contayning England, France, Spaine, &c.
Eurybatiziſe. To ſteale things in a houſe.
Exact. Earneſtly to demand, or perfect.
Exaction. A taking vp of money by conſtraint.
Exareanate. To waſh off grauell, or ſand.
Exaturate. To fill a hungry ſtomacke.
Exaugurate. To make prophane, to vnhallow.
Exauthorate. To put men of warre out of wages.
Exauſpicate. To doe a thing vnluckily.
Excaecate. To put out ones eye.
Excalceate. To put off ones ſhooes.
Excadencie. Anger which both ſuddenly commeth and goeth.
Excerebrate. To beat out ones braines.
Exceſſe. Too much of any thing.
Excommunicate. To thruſt one out of the holy aſſembly.
Excreate. To retch, or ſpit out.
Excrement. Any thing which naturally growes in the body, which may bee taken away without any harme thereto.
Excreation. A retching or ſpitting out.
Excreable. Which eaſily may be ſpit out.
Excreſcion. A ſwelling or growing in the fleſh.
Exdorſicate. To breake the backe bone.
Exemplarie. Of, or belonging to an example.
Exemplifie. To declare a thing at large.
Exemption. A freedome from any ſeruice.
Exemptible. Which may be eaſily taken away.
Exenterate. To take out the bowels of beaſts.
Exequies. Funerals in honour of the dead.
Exhale. To caſt out a breath, or fume.
Exhalation. A fumie ſmoake, hot & dry, drawne out of the earth by the heat of the Sunne.
Exhauſt. To draw out, conſume or ſpend.
Exherbe. To take herbs from any place.
Exhibilate. To hiſſe or whiſtle after.
Exigent. A ſtreight, a hard pinch.
Exiſt. To appeare, or be.Exiſtence. An appearing or being.
Exoculate. To put out ones eye.
Exodium. An end, or the ending of a thing.
Exorbitant. A going out of the right way.
Exordium. The firſt entrance of a Sermon, or ſo.
Expapillate. To lay the breaſts open to the paps.
Expediate. To diſpatch, or make ready.
Expergefie. To awake one out of his ſleepe.
Expiable. Which may be ſatisfied for.
Explement. Any thing that filleth vp.
Explode. To driue out with clapping of hands.
Expoſe. To ſet to view, to ſet abroad.
Expoſtulate. To reaſon angerly with one.
Expreſſion. A ſqueezing or preſſing out.
Exprobate. To caſt in ones teeth.
Exprobation. A caſting in ones teeth.
Expugne. To winne by an aſſault.
Extant. Which is ſet forth to view.
Extercorate. To empt, or carry out dung.
Extimulate. To moue one to anger.
Extinguiſh. To quench, to put out.
Extorque. To wreſt from one perforce.
Extortion. Wrong done by taking greater fees then the Law allowes of.
Extricable. Which may be rid, or auoyded.
Extrinſecall. Outward, or on the outſide.
Extuberate. To ſwell like the ſea.
Exuberate. To abound, to beare in great abundance.
Exululate. To howle, to cry out for pitty.
Exuſcitate. To awake one vp from ſleepe.

list.head: F
list.item: Faction. A ſect, or diuiſion into ſundry opinions.
Factor. Which ſelleth or buyeth for a Merchant.
Falſitie. Falſehood, lying.Famigerate. To report abroad.
Faſtigate. To ſharpen a thing vpward.
Fatall. Which commeth to paſſe by chance.
Fealtie. A ceremonie done by ſome tenants to the Lord of whom they hold lands: which is, in laying their right hand vpon a booke, and promiſing fidelitie to him by oath.
Fell. Sometime it ſignifieth a skinne, cruell, and terrible, and ſometime to cut.
Feminine. Of, or belonging to the femall kinde.

Fenchmonth. A moneth wherein Does doe Fawne, it begins about the ninth of Iune, and continueth vntill the ninth of Iuly, in which time it is not lawfull to hunt in any Forreſt. In the Fenchmonth, it is not lawfull for any Cart of Paniers to paſſe through any Forreſt without paying fees: which fee, for a paire of Wheeles is foure pence, and for Paniers two pence, which fee being once paid they may for that ſeaſon freely paſſe.
Foenerate. To put money to vſurie.
Feodary. An officer who is to bee preſent with the Eſcheater at the finding of any office, and to ſuruey lands, and to rate them.

Feofment. A deed witneſſing the ſale or gift of lands in fee ſimple, with liuerie of ſeiſin and poſſeſſion thereof: hee that maketh the Feofment is called the Feofer, and the party to whom it is made the Feofee.
Ferula. A ſticke to ſtrike ſchollars on the hand.

Feuer hecticke. A feuer
that burnes one inwardly, and makes cold without.
Figuratiue. Which ſerueth for the repreſentation of another thing.
Figurate. To forme or faſhion a thing.
Filiall. Of, or belonging to a ſonne.
Fine. An end: ſometimes when one takes land for yeeres, tis money paide preſently in hand.
Finall. Of, or belonging to an end.
Fiſtulate. To ramme or beat downe ſtones.
Fluxibilitie. Aptneſſe to flow or ſpread.
Fluxible. Which is apt to flow.
Foines. A kind of furre, the top whereof is blacke, and the ground whitiſh, the beaſt that beareth it, is about the bigneſſe of a Cat.
Folio. A ſheete or leafe of paper.

Foeteſtall. The lower part
of a pillar whereon it ſtandeth.
Forcer. A Coffer, a ſmall Cheſt.
Foreſtall. To buy any Merchandize by the highway, ere it come into the marquet for to regrate it againe.
Formalitie. An obſeruing of good order.
Formidable. Cruell, fearefull to looke on.
Fortification. Any place made ſtrong, a hold.
Fragment. A broken peece, a cantle.
Fraxate. To goe view the watch.
Front. The firſt part of a battell, the forehead.
Frontiſpice. The forepart of a Booke, or Houſe.
Frontiere. The bounds or limits of a Countrey.
Frontlet. Any thing worne on the forehead.
Frumentation. A generall dole of Corne.
Fugitiue. One likely to runne away.
Fulcible. Which may be propped vp.
Function. An office, or courſe of life.
Fundamentall. Of, or belonging to a foundation.
Funeſtate. To pollute with a dead body, to ſtaine.
Future. That which ſhall come hereafter.

list.head: G
list.item: Gabions. Baskets full of earth, to keepe off great • unnes.
Galactopoton. One that ſtill drinkes milke.
Gallemaufrey. A confuſed heape of things together.
Gallulate. To beginne to haue a big voice.
Gangean colour. Diuers colours in one together, as in a Mallard or Pigeons necke.
Garble. To cleanſe things from duſt.
Gargariſme. A liquor to waſh ones mouth.
Genitals. The priuie members of any thing.
Genius. A good angell, or a familiar euill ſpirit, the ſoule.
Gentill. One which profeſſeth not the faith of Chriſt.
Gentiliſme. The beleefe of the Gentils.
Geographie. A deſcription of the earth.
Geomancie. Diuination by circles in the earth.
Geometrie. A meaſuring on the earth.Geometricean. One skilfull in Geometrie.
Georgicks. Books ſpeaking of husbandry and tillage.
Gerah. The twentieth part of a Shekle.
Geſticulation. A moouing of the fingers, hands, or othet parts, either in idle wantonneſſe, or to expreſſe ſome matter by ſignes, in dancing, ſinging, or the like.
Geſts. Noble acts, commonly of Princes.
Gingreate. To chirpe as birds doe.
Glabreate. To make plaine or ſmoothe.
Glabretall. A bare ſplat in the earth.
Glaciate. To be frozen, to turne to Ice.
Glacitate. To cry like a gander.
Glaucitate. To cry like a whelpe,
Glocidate. To clocke like a Hen.
Globe. A round bowle, or the deſcriptiō of the world, made in ſuch a forme.
Gloſſe. A ſhort expoſition of any darke ſpeech.
Gloſſographer. He which expoundeth ſtrange words.
Gloſſographie. An expounding of ſtrange words.
Glow. To be hot or red.
Glucupicron. A hotchpotch or pel-mel of things.
Gnarre. A hard knot in wood, a chub, or churle.
Gnoffe, A churle, a foole, a chub.
Goldfoyld. A thinne leafe of gold.
Golden number. A number deuiſed to finde out the feaſt of Eaſter.
Goliardize. He that hath a great large mouth.
Golgotha. A place of dead mens ſculls.
Gomer. A meaſure containing fifteene gallons.
Gonorrhea. The running of the reines.
Gordian knot. A knot which cannot be vndone.
Gourmondize. Gluttonie, to eate like a Glutton.
Graduate. He that hath taken a degree of learning in a publike Vniuerſitie.
Grammaticall. Of, or belonging to Grammar.
Grangrene. A diſeaſe when fleſh waxeth dead by degrees.
Gratifie. To pleaſure one, or requite a courteſie.
Gratuitie. A reward, or gift giuen freely.
Gratulate. To ſhew ones ioy in anothers felicitie.
Gratulation. A ioying in anothers good.
Graunge. A lone houſe in the Countrey, a Village.
Guſt. To taſte, ſometimes a great puffe of winde.
Gymnaſticke. A teacher of the Wraſtling Science.

list.head: H
list.item: HAberdepoiſe. A pound weight of ſixteene ounces.
Habitable. Which may be dwelt in.
Habituall. Growne to a cuſtome by long vſe.
Halituous. Vaporous, moiſt, thi • ne, which may bee voided out by the pores.
Hamkin. A pudding made vpon a ſhoulder of Mutton, all the fleſh being firſt taken off.
Hamlet. A Village in the Countrey.

Hague. A hand-gun about three quarters of a
yard in length.
Harbinger. One taking vp lodgings for others.
Hariant. A terme in Haraldry, when a fiſh is painted ſtanding vpright.
Harmonie. Delightfull muſicke of many notes.
Harquebuze. A Hand gun, ſhorter, but bigger and heauier than a Muſquet.
Harquebuſier. Hee that ſhooteth in it.
Harrow. An old word ſignifying away, fie.
Hauſelins. An old word for breeches.
Hearſe. A buriall coffin, couered with blacke.
Hecatombe. A ſacrifice wherein were offered one hundred beaſts.
Hecaton cheron. One hauing an hundred hands.
Hemiſphere. That part of the Heauens which is ſtill to vs viſible.
Henchman. A Page of honor attending on a Prince.
H • nt. To catch or lay hold on.
Herball. A booke of the nature of herbs.
Hereticall. In a falſe beleefe, obſtinate.
Hereticke. He which maketh choice of himſelfe what points of Religion he will beleeue, and what hee will not.
Hereditarie. That which commeth to one by inheritance.
Heriot. The beſt liuing beaſt which a tenant hath at his death, which in ſome Manors is due to the Lord of whom he holds it.

Hermophrodite. Which is
both man and woman.
Hermite. A ſolitary dwelling in the wilderneſſe, attending onely to deuotion.
Hermitage. A lone houſe wherein a Hermite dwelleth.
Heroycke. The ſame that Heroycall is.
Heteroclite. A Noune which is otherwiſe declined then other Nounes are.
Hewte. A little copſe, or groue.
Hexameter. A verſe of ſix feet.
Hibride. A Hog ingendred betweene a wilde Boare and a tame Sow.
Hide of land. Some ſay it is one hundred acres.
Hidage. A tax for euery hide of land.
Hide-bound. A diſeaſe in Cattell, when the skin doth cleaue to their ſides.
Hiera-picra. A bitter confection made of Aloſuccotrina, to purge melancholicke humours.

Hierar • hie. The holy order of Angels, which containing nine degrees (as ſome write) is a myſticall reſemblance of the Trinitie, there being in nine thrice three, and in euery three thrice one; ſo that there are three ſuperiours, three inferiours, and three middle degrees: the ſuperiour are Seraphins; Cherubins, and Thrones; the middle are Dominations, Principalities, Powers; the Inferiour, Vertues, Archangels and Angels.

Hieroglyphicks. A myſticall kinde of writing, vſed in ancient time by Pagans, Prieſts, and the like: This kinde of writing was by making the forme of beaſts and the like, and could hardly bee vnderſtood (eſpecially of the vulgar ſort) without great knowledge of the nature of things: As for example, eternitie they expreſſed by a round circle which hath no end: a King, by a Scepter, with an eye in the top thereof: a matter of haſte, by a Dolphin, the ſwifteſt of all Fiſhes: and a matter of aduice or deliberation, by an Anchor which ſtaies a ſhip in the waues, with a thouſand ſuch deuices not ſubiect to common capacities to finde out.
Hilarode. A ſinger of wanton ſongs.
Hin. A meaſure containing foure pottles and a quart.
Hippace. A Cheeſe made of Mares-milke.
Hippomanean fleſh. Looke Colts fleſh in the other booke.
Hircipill. Whoſe haire is of two ſorts.
Hirquiticke. One paſt foureteene yeeres of age, beginning to bee moued with Venus delight.
Hiſtoricall. Of, or belonging to Hiſtories.
Hiſtrionicie. The Art to play enterludes.
Hoane. A fine kinde of Wherſtone.

Hogſteere. A wilde Boore
of three yeeres old.
Holocauſt. A Sacrifice wherein the whole beaſt is offered, and no part thereof reſerued.
Holograph. A Teſtament all written by the Teſtators hands.
Homage. A ſeruile ceremonie of ſome tenants, which by dutie they owe to their Lords.
Homonymie. A logicall terme, when one word ſignifies diuers things: As for example, Fell ſignifies a skinne, as alſo cruell or fierce, and likewiſe, to cut or hew any thing.
Honour-point. The vpper part of a Scutchion, when the bredth thereof is diuided into three euen parts.
Honeſtate. To honor, to ſet forth.
Hopeſteere. A Pilot to guide a ſhip.
Hord. A Cow great with Calfe.
Horizon. A circle diuiding the ouerpart of Heauen from the other halfe.
Horoſcope. Wherin houres bee marked, as in a dyall: alſo the place of the firmament that riſeth euery houre from the Eaſt.
Horripilate. To grow rough with haire.
Hoſanna. Saue now, I beſeech thee.
Hoſtage. A pledge left in warres for performance.
Hoſtile. Of, or belonging to an enemie.
Hotchpot. A mingling together of things, but eſpecially of lands.
Howſell. To miniſter the Communion to one that lyeth on his death-bed.
Huke. A Dutch attire, couering the head, face, and all the body.
Hulke. To take out the garbage of a Hare or conie.
Humane. Gentle, pertaining to a man.
Hybridan. Whoſe parents are of diuers and ſundry Nations.
Hydragoge. He that bringeth water to any place by furrowes and trenches.
Hydromancie. Diuination by calling damned ſpirits to appeare in the water.
Hydropoticke. One that ſtill drinkes water.
Hyemall. Of, or belonging to winter.
Hyemate. To winter at a place.
Hyperbole. A figure who • one ſpeaketh a great deale more than is preciſely true.
Hyperbolicall. Any thing ſpoken aboue all beleefe; as to ſay, harder than a Diamond, or ſwifter than thought, &c. is called an Hyperbolicall ſpeech.
Hyſtorologie. An altering of the order of ſpeech, by placing that after that ſhould be before.
Hyſteron & Proteron. The Cart before the Horſe.

list.head: I
list.item: Iacobs ſtaffe. An inſtrument in Geometrie.
Iaculatorie. That which is ſuddenly caſt from one like a dart.
Iambes. Poſts ſuſtaining both ſides of a doore.
Ichnographie. The deſcription of a building, which one is about to make.
Idea. The forme of any thing conceiued in the minde.
Idiome. The forme of any ſpeech.
Idiote. A foole, an vnlearned Aſſe.

Ides. Eight daies in euery moneth, ſo called, for becauſe they diuide the moneth almoſt in the middle; in March, May, Iuly and October, theſe eight daies beginne at the eight day of the moneth, and continue to the fifteenth: in all other moneths they begin at the ſixt day, and continue to the thirteenth: where note that the laſt day onely is called Ides.
Ieboua. The vnſpeakable name of God.
Ieiunitie. Barrenneſſe, or ſlenderneſſe of ſtile.
A booke written • n Greeke by Homer, of the deſtruction of Troy.
Illatrate. To ſcoffe or barke at a thing.
Illuſtrate. To make famous, or noble.
Illutible. That cannot be waſhed away.
Imagerie. Painted or carued workes of Images.
Imaginarie. That which is conceiued in the minde.

Immediate. That which commeth directly from
one thing to another.
Immigrate. To goe dwell in ſome place.
Immit. To ſend in, to put in.
Immiſſion. A putting, or ſending in.
Immodulate. To doe a thing without due proportion.
Immure. To wall or ſhut vp.
Imparadiz'd. To enioy all true content.
Imparlance. When one ſued in the common Law for debt, or the like, craueth of the Court ſome reſpit of time before hee put in his anſwer.
Impaſſibilitie. No feeling of any paine.
Impenitrable. Not to bee pierced through.
Impertinent. Not belonging to the matter.
Impietie. Wickedneſſe, a deſpiſing of God, &c.
Implicate. To intangle, to wrappe in.
Implication. A wrapping in or intangling.
Importunitie. Too much earneſtneſſe in asking.
Impoſt. Cuſtome payed at any place.
Impoſtume. A quantitie of euill humours, or bloud gathered together in ſome part of the body.
Imprecate. To curſe, or wiſh one ill.
Impreſſa. A deuice painted vpon a ſhield.
Impreſſe. To import the forme of a thing.
Impropriation. An Eccleſiaſticall liuing, comming to one by inheritance.
Imputation. A coniecturall laying to ones charge.
Impute. To lay to ones charge.
Imputatiue. Which is imputed to one.
Inacceſſible. Which cannot be come vnto.
Inamiable. Vnpleaſant, not to be beloued.
Inargentate. To gilt or couer with ſiluer.
Inate. Naturall, which is borne with one.
Inaurated. Gilted, or couered with gold.
Incapable. Which cannot conceiue, a foole.
Incendiarie. Which ſetteth any thing on fire.
Incenſe. To ſtirre vp to anger.
Incernate. To couer with wax, to ſeere.
Inceſt. Carnall knowledge betwixt neere kindred.
Incident. Which happeneth or belongeth to a thing.
Incline. To bend or bow downe.
Include. To containe, to ſhut in.
Inconcuſſed. Stable, not to be ſhaken.
Incordiate. To put into ones heart.
Incorporate. To mix two or moe ſubſtances together.
Incredible. Whieh is not to be beleeued.
Inculcate. To repeate a thing often.
Incumbent. One in poſſeſſion of a ſpirituall liuing.
Incurſion. A running in, a meeting together.
Indefeaſable. Not to bee withſtood or gaine-ſaid.
Indeleble. Not to bee razed out.
Indeprecable. That will not be entreated.
Index. A Table in a booke.
Indigitate. To call, to ſhew with pointing the finger.
Indiuiduall. Not to bee parted, as man and wife.
Indubitate. To doubt nothing at all.
Induction. A drawing in, or a forme of an argument proceeding from particulars to vniuerſals.
Ineffable. Not to bee ſpoken of.
Inelaborate. To doe a thing curiouſly.
Ineluctable. Not to bee ouercome by any paines.
Inequalitie. Things being not euen, or vnlike.
Inequitable. Not to bee rid through.
Inexpiable. Which cannot bee ſatisfied for.
Inextirpable. Not to be rooted out.
Inextricable. So confuſed that a man cannot winde himſelfe out of.
Inexuperable. Not to bee paſſed ouer.
Inferre. To bring in by way of argument.
Inference. A concluding on ſome thing going before.
Inflation. A puffing vp with wind.
Inflect. To bow, to make crooked.
Inflict. To lay puniſhment vpon one.

Influence. A flowing in, power which Planets
and ſtarres haue ouer inferiour things.
Infricate. To rub in, or vpon.
Infume. To dry in the ſmoake.
Ingeniculate. To curchie, to bow the knee.
Ingenuated. One borne of honeſt ſtocke, noble kindred.
Ingeſtible. Heauie, hard to be borne.
Ingot. A ſmall wedge of fined gold.
Ingredience. A going in, or that which goeth into the making of a thing.
Ingroſſe. To buy all for ones ſelfe, or to write a thing faire.
Ingroſſer. That buyeth corne ſtanding in the field, or dead victuals to ſell againe.
Inguſtible. Not to be ſwallowed vp.
Inhabitable. Not to bee dwelt in.
Inhance. To raiſe the price of things.
Inherent. Cleauing to, or abiding in a thing.
Iniunction. An enioyning one to doe a thing.
Innatible. Not to bee ſwimmed in.
Innauigable. Not to bee ſailed in.
Inobſeruable. Which cannot well be noted.
Inquilinate. To dwell in a ſtrange place.

row.cell: Not to be ſatisfied or filled

list.item: Inſcription. A note written vpon any thing.
Inſectation. A rayling, or ſpeaking ill of one.
Inſection. A declaration, or long continuance.
Inſenſible. Which cannot bee perceiued, or one ſo fooliſh that perceiueth nothing.
Inſert. To adde, to put in.
Inſidious. One lying in wait, to ſuppreſſe another.
Inſinuate. To creepe into ones fauour.
Inſinuation. A cunning ſpeech to creepe into ones fauour.
Inſolation. A drying in the ſunne.
Inſomnie. Watching, want of power to ſleepe.
Inſociable. Not fit to keep any companie.
Inſpirable. One paſt all hope, vnlookt for.
Inſtance. An example brought of a thing.
Inſtant. Very earneſt, or the preſent time.
Inſurrection. A riſing of men in armes.
Intercede. To ſtep betweene, to intreat for one.
Interception. A taking by the way.
Interceſſion. An intreaty in ones behalfe.
Interciſion. An intreating in ones behalfe.
Intercluded. A paſſage or ſluce ſhut vp.
Intercluſion. A ſhutting vp of a ſluce.
Intercourſe. Paſſing or ſending one to another.
Intereſt. Right or title, profit made by vſury.
Interfeere. To knocke the legs together in going.
Interiected. A caſting or laying betweene.
Interlace. To ioyne, to mix together.
Interline. To write betweene two written lines.
Intermediate. Speech, a thing ſpoken betwixt.
Intermiſſion. A leauing off for a time.
Intermit. To leaue off for a time.
Intermix. To mingle with other things.
Internecation. A ſlaughter where none eſcape.
Interpellation. An interrupting of one while hee ſpeakes.
Interpoſe. To buſie ones ſelfe where he needs not.
Interreigne. That ſpace of time betwixt the old King and the new.
Interrex. Hee that gouernes while there is no King.
Interrogation. An asking of a queſtion.
Interuall. Diſtance of time and place.
Interuigilate. To watch now and then.
Inteſtate. Which dies without making a will.
Intromit. To put or let in.
Inuade. To aſſault, to ſet vpon.
Inuectiue. A ſpeech made in diſgrace of one.
Inueigh. Bitterly to ſpeake againſt one.
Inuentorie. A writing of qualitie, and value of ones goods.
Inuerſion. A turning vp fide downe.
Inuert. To turne vp ſide downe.
Inueſtigation. A finding out by tracing.
Inuite. To requeſt one to a ſupper, or ſo.
Inuncate. To incroach, to hooke, to intangle.
Inuolate. To flie into ſome place.
Inuolue. To role vp in a thing.
Inurinate. To waſh or plunge, as Geeſe doe.
Iraſcible. Hauing power to be angry.
Ironie. Speaking by contraries, ſaying blacke is white.
Irregularitie. A going out of right rule.
Irremiable. Which cannot be returned from.
Irreuocable. Not to bee called backe.
Irrigate. To water ground, or ſo.
Iſtmos. A narrow part of a Countrey betweene two Seas.
Iterate. To repeat or doe againe.
Iubilation. A great ſhout for ioy.
Iubilie. A reioycing yeer, ſometime euery hundred yeere, ſometime euery fiftie yeere, ſometime euery twentie yeere.
Iudaiſme. The beleefe of the Iewes.

row.cell: Of, or belonging to iudgement, graue, wiſe, of great iudgement.

list.item: Iugulation. A cutting of ones throat.
Iulian moneth. The moneth of Iuly.
Iuridicall. Of, or belonging to iudgement.
Iuriſdiction. Lawfull authoritie in any place.

list.head: K.
list.item: Karos. A drowſie diſeaſe in the head.
Keele. The bottome of a ſhip.
Kirat. The weight of three graines.
Knight ſeruice. An ancient tenure of lands, by which a man was bound to beare armes in warre for the defence of the realme.

list.head: L.
list.item: Labyrinth. An intricate building, or an endleſſe worke.
Lachanize. To faint, to wax feeble.
Lachanopoll. Which ſelleth herbs, or herb market.
Lacunate. To make ditches or holes.
Laetable. Worthy to bee reioyced at.
Laetificate. To reioyce.Leuigate. To poliſh ſmoothe, to plaine.
Lake. A faire red colour vſed by Painters.
Laitie. Lay men, their eſtate or degree.
Lallate. To ſpeake babylike, or childiſhly.
Lanuge. Downe, or the beard when it firſt appeares to grow.
Latibulate. Priuily to hide ones ſelfe in a corner.
Latitude. Largeneſſe, the bredth of any thing.
Latibule. A denne, or lurking place.
Latrate. To barke like a dog.
Latrator. Which barketh, or rayleth, or ſcoffeth.
Latrocinate. To rob, to play the theefe.
Lauatrine. A ſquare ſtone in a Kitchin, with a hole to auoid water, a ſincker.
Laurell. The Bay tree, or garland of Bayes.
Laxate. To releaſe, to looſe, to pardon.
Lazer. A leper, one full of ſcabs.
Leconomancie. Diuination by water in a baſon.
Leede. An old name of the moneth of March.
Leete. A Court or Lawday, held commonly euery halfe yeere.
Legacie. Any thing giuen by will.
Legall. Of, or belonging to the Law.
Legendarie. A booke of old hiſtories.
Legion. An armie, containing both of Horſe and Foot 6826.
Leſſee. He that taketh a leaſe.
Leſſes. Dung of ſome rauenous beaſt, Wolfe, or Beare, &c.
Leſſour. Which ſetteth out lands to another.
Leuament. The comfort which one hath of his wife.
Libertine. One of a looſe life.
Licitation. An inhauncing of a price ſet vpon any thing that is ſold.
Lieu. In ſtead, or place of another.
Lignation. A hewing or purueying of wood.
Lignum vitae. A wood much vſed in Phyſicke againſt the French diſeaſe.
Lineament. The proportion of the body.
Lineall. Downe right like a line.
Lippitude. The diſeaſe of the eies.
Lithoglyphicke. A grauer or cutter of ſtones.
Litargie. The foame that riſeth from Lead when its tryed.
Litigate. To contend in Law with one.
Liturgie. The publike ſeruice of the Church.
Locall. Of, or belonging to a place.
Location. A placing, a ſetting out to hire.
Locitate. To ſet, or let out to hire.
Lodeſtarre. A ſtarre that guideth one.
Longitude. The length of a thing.
Lorament. A thong or band made of leather.
Loricate. To arme one with a coat of defence.
Loſſell. A crafty fellow, a lowt.
Lucible. That which is light of its ſelfe.
Lucrate. To winne, or gaine, or get.
Lucubration. A working by that light.
Lunacie. A diſeaſe, when at certaine times of the Moone one is diſtracted in his wits.
Lutament. A wall or bridge made of morter.
Luxate. To put out of ioynt.
Lymphaticall. One diſtracted by a viſion.
Lyncius-eyes. One quick and cleere ſighted.

list.head: M
list.item: MAcerate. To ſoake in water, to make leane.
Maceration. A ſoaking or making leane.
Machination. A ſubtill deuiſing of a matter.
Maculation. A blemiſhing, or infamie, or reproch.
Memacterian Moneth. The moneth of September.
Magnalls. Great things to be wondered at.
Magnanimous. Which is noble and ſtout of heart.
Magnipend. Much to eſteeme or ſet by.
Mainepernours. Sureties for one to appeare before a Iudge at a certaine day.
Maineprize. The bayling of one out of priſon vpon ſecuritie giuen, that hee ſhall be forth comming.
Maior. The greater, or more ancient.
Malagme. A rotting or riping plaiſter.
Malleable. Which may be beaten with a hammer.
Manalean gate. The gate through which the ſoules of the dead paſſe from Hell to Heauen.
Manduble. The iaw-bone wherein the teeth be ſet.
Mangonize. To poliſh for better ſale.
Mangonie. The Art to make things ſaleable.
Manie. A diſeaſe in the head cal'd madneſſe.
Manna. Foode which God gaue the Iſraelites from Heauen, white and much like Coriander ſeed.
Manuall. Which may be carried in the hand.
Manubiarie. One that hath part of the prey.
Manubie. Spoile gotten from the enemie.
Manumiſſion. A making one free from bondage.
Marches. Bounds lying betweene two Countries.
Marchioneſſe. The wife of a Marques.
Marginate. To make brimmes, or margents.
Maronian wine. Wine of ſuch vertue and ſtrength, that if twentie times ſo much water be put into it, it will ſtill notwithſtanding keepe his vertue.
Mart. A great faire or market.
Martyr. One that dies for Religions ſake.

Martyrdome. A ſuffering of grieuous torment vnto
the death for conſtant perſeuerance in true Religion.
Matyrologie. A booke of the memory of Martyrs.
Maſſacre. A murdering of many together.
Maſtuprate. Diſhoneſtly to touch ones priuities.
Materiall. Which hath ſubſtance in it.
Materiation. The ſelling of timber for building.
Mathematicean. One that is skilled in Augurie, Geometrie, and Aſtronomie.
Mathematicks. The Arts of Arithmaticke, Muſicke, Geometrie, Geographie, Aſtronomie, Aſtrologie, and Coſmographie.
Matrimoniall. Of, or belonging to mariage.
Matrix. The wombe or place of conception.
Maugre. In deſpight of ones heart.
Maxime. A true and generall rule.
Mazar. A broad flat cup to drinke in; it is alſo a kinde of Cherry.
Maze. An aſtoniſhment, it is alſo a deuice in a Garden, like a labyrinth, made in manner of a knot, wherein if one enter hee can hardly get forth.
Mechanicall. Of, or belonging to a Crafts-man.
Mediate. To make an indifferent end, or an attonement betwixt two aduerſaries.
Mediation. A meanes of agreement by a friend to both parties.
Medicinall. Of, or belonging to Phyſicke.
Mediterranean Sea. A ſea parting Europe from Africa.
Melancholy. The groſſeſt of the foure corporall humours, which if it abound too much, cauſeth heauineſſe and ſadnes of minde.
Mellation. The driuing of Bees to get out the Honie.
Membrane. The thinne skinne and vpmoſt of any part of the body.
Memorandum. A terme vſed when wee write any thing we would not forget.
Memorate. To make mention of a thing.
Memoriall. Which putteth one in remembrance.
Menſtruous. Hauing her ſickneſſe, foule, filthy.
Mentall. That which is only thought in the minde.
Mercenarie. A hireling, one working for hire.
Meridean. Of, or belonging to noone tide.
Meridiation. A ſleeping at noone tide.
Meſonoxian. Of, or belonging to midnight.
Meſſias. Annointed, Chriſt is often ſo called.
Metamorphoſis. A change from one ſhape to another.
Metaphore. The changing of a word from the naturall ſenſe, into another ſenſe like vnto it.
Metator. Hee which ſetteth in order.
Meteore. An elementary body, as Snow, Haile, Clouds, Winds, Blazingſtarres, Thunder, Lightening, and the like.
Meteorologon. One ſtudious of coeleſtiall things.
Meter. Meaſure, or a Verſe made by meaſure.
Methode. A direct way to teach.
Methodiz'd. Brought into a good order of teaching.
Metonymie. A figure when the cauſe is put for the effect, the ſubiect for the adiunct, or contrarily.
Metropolitan. The chiefe Citie, or Biſhop.
Migration. Flitting from one place to another.
Migrate. To flit here and there.
Mimigraph. A writer of wanton matters.
Mina. The weight of threeſcore Sheckles.
Minerall. Metall, or any thing dig'd out of the earth.
Miniuer. Fine white furre made of a Squerils belly.
Minoritie. A mans time before he be full age to diſpoſe of his goods or lands.
Minurize. To ſing ſmall, to faine in ſinging.
Miſanthrophon. One that hates mans company.
Miſimpriſion. A miſtaking of the meaning or ſenſe of one word for another.
Miſocall. One hating all honeſt dealings.
Miſſiue. That which witneſſeth ones being ſent.
Mithridate. An excellent confection made by King Mithridates, to expell poyſon.
Mittimus. A warrant made to conuey an offendor to priſon.
Moderne. Liuing now in our age.
Modulation. A ſinging by meaſure, ſweet ſinging.
Mollification. A making ſumple or ſoft.
Moloch. An Idoll like a Calfe, to whom the Iſraelites did offer their children in ſacrifice of fire.
Momentanie. During for a ſmall time.
Monarch. A King, Prince, or the like.
Monarchie. The rule of one Prince alone.
Monarchize. To beare a great rule, &c.
Monaſterie. A religious houſe of Monkes.
Monogamie. Such as haue had but one wife.
Monologie. A long tale of little worth.
Monoma • hie. A combat of two hand to hand.
Monopolie. When one ingroſſeth commodities in ſuch faſhion that none can ſell them, or gaine by them but himſelfe onely.
Moote. To reaſon or argue a cauſe in Law.
Morall. Of, or belonging to good manners.
Morgage. To pawne lands, houſes, or goods.
Morigerate. To doe as one is commanded, to obey.
Mortification. A killing, or taking away of ones pleaſure.
Mortuarie. Payment due for buriall of the dead.
Mother. A diſeaſe in women when the wombe riſeth with paine vpwards: ſweet ſmelles are ill for it, but loathſome ſauors good.
Motion. A mouing from place to place.
Motiue. A cauſe mouing one to doe a thing.
Mott. A ſhort ſentence, a word.
Mountebancke. A baſe deceitfull Merchant (chiefly of drugs) which with impudent lying, doth for the moſt part, ſell counterfeit ſtuffe to the common people.
Mulct. A fine, or penaltie layed on one.
Mulieroſitie. The vice of louing many women.
Multate. To puniſh by the purſe.
Mummia. A thing like Pitch, ſome ſay it is made of mans-fleſh boild in Pitch; Others, that it is taken out of old Tombes, being a corrupted humour that droppeth from embalmed bodies.
Municipall. Belonging to the eſtate of a Free-man or Burgeſſe of a Citie.
Munition. Great ordnance for warre, or ſhot.
Muſſitate. To ſpeake through the teeth.
Mutuall. That which paſſeth one from another.
Muzrole. An Iron band which comes ouer a horſes noſe.
Myriarch. A captaine of ten thouſand.
Myſticall. Darke, which hath a myſterie in it.
Mythologie. An expoſition of Poets riddles.

list.head: N
list.item: NAdir. The point of the Heauens right vnder our feet.
Naperie. Fine linnen for the table.
Narcoticall. Which hath power to make the body inſenſible.
Narrable. That which may be declared.
Natiue. That place where one is borne, naturall.
Nauigible. Which may be ſayled in.
Naumachie. A battell or fight at ſea.
Nauſtible. A Port or Haven for ſhips.

Nazarite. The Iewes ſo called thoſe that vowed themſelues ſometime to God, and while their vow laſted, they abſtained from all kinde of Wine, nor could they drinke any thing which might make them drunke, they neuer cut their haire, but did ſuffer it ſtill to grow: their vow expired, they preſented themſelues to the Prieſts, who offered a Sacrifice for them, and then was their haire cut, and burnt therewith, and then they might drinke any thing, as before.
Necromancie. Diuination by calling vp Deuils, or dead mens ghoſts.
Nectar. A pleaſant liquor, which Poets faine the gods did drinke.
Necyomantie. Diuination by calling vp damned ſpirits.
Neophyte. Any thing newly planted or ſet, one newly conuerted to the faith, a nouice.
Nepenthe. An herbe, being ſteept in Wine and drunke, expels ſadneſſe.
Neuter. An indifferent partie, not in one ſide nor the other.
Neutralitie. A retchleſſe being on neither ſide.
Nictation. The twinckling of the eye.
Nocturnall. Of, or belonging to the night.
Nocturne. Prayers vſed at certain houres of the night.
Noli me tangere. The French diſeaſe.
Nonage. Vnder 21. yeeres old, a childe.
Nonreſidencie. Vnlawfull abſence from the place of ones abode.
Nonreſident. Which is abſent from the place where he ought to be.

Nones. Are ſix daies next following the firſt day in March, May, Iuly, and October, in the other moneths, foure daies next after the firſt, but the laſt of theſe daies is properly called Nones, and the other reckoned backwards, according to the number diſtant from the Nones: They are called Nones becauſe they are iuſt nine daies before the Ides.
Nonſuit. The letting fall of a ſuit.

Nouice. A young learner
without experience.
Nugament. A bable, toy, or lie.
Nullifidean. One of no account or Religion.
Nundinate. To buy and ſell, as at faires.

list.head: O
list.item: Obganiate. To trouble one with often repeating of one thing.
Obiect. That which is placed before ones eyes.
Obiection. A laying to ones charge.
